    "The \"Checkers speech\" was a landmark televised address delivered by **Richard Nixon on September 23, 1952**, while he was the Republican nominee for Vice President of the United States[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech).\n\nThe speech is famous for its emotional appeal, its masterful use of the emerging medium of television, and its role in saving Nixon\u2019s political career.\n[3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)\n### Why the Speech Was Given\nDuring the 1952 presidential campaign, Nixon faced intense scrutiny following reports that he had maintained a \"secret fund\" established by his political backers to reimburse him for travel and other political expenses. [1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech)Although the fund was technically legal, it became a major political liability, and many in the Republican Party\u2014including presidential nominee Dwight D. Eisenhower\u2014considered dropping Nixon from the ticket due to concerns over his integrity.\n\n###[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [5](http://users.wfu.edu/zulick/454/checkers.html) Content of the Speech\nNixon chose to bypass traditional press channels and take his case directly to the American public via a 30-minute television broadcast. Key [1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)elements of the address included:\n*   **Defense of Finances:** Nixon provided a detailed (and, at the time, rare) disclosure of his personal finances to prove he had not personally enriched himself.\n*   [6](https://www.britannica.com/topic/Checkers-speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)**The \"Checkers\" Anecdote:** To humanize himself, he spoke about his family and their modest lifestyle. He f[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech)amously mentioned a gift his children had received: a black-and-white Cocker Spaniel named **Checkers**. He d[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech)eclared that, regardless of what anyone said, the family intended to keep the dog.\n*   [1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)**Call to Action:** He urged viewers to contact the Republican National Committee to share their opinion on whether he should remain on the ticket.\n\n###[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech) Why It Is Important\n*   **Saved His Career:** The speech triggered an overwhelming wave of public support, which convinced Eisenhower to keep Nixon on the ticket.\n*   [1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checkers_speech), [3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech)**Television in Politics:** It is widely considered a turning point in political communication. It d[3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)emonstrated the enormous power of television to allow a candidate to bypass the media and connect directly with millions of voters in their own homes.\n*   [3](https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/history/nixons-checkers-speech), [4](https://www.nixonfoundation.org/2016/09/how-checkers-changed-the-game-of-television/)**Political Legacy:** While effective at the time, the speech\u2014particularly its sentimental tone\u2014eventually became a subject of ridicule and criticism in 